text: Disney's "Muppets Most Wanted" takes the entire Muppets gang on a global tour, selling out grand theaters in some of Europe's most exciting destinations, including Berlin, Madrid and London. But mayhem follows the Muppets overseas, as they find themselves unwittingly entangled in an international crime caper headed by Constantine—the World's Number One Criminal and a dead ringer for Kermit—and his dastardly sidekick Dominic, aka Number Two, portrayed by Ricky Gervais. The film stars Tina Fey as Nadya, a feisty prison guard, and Ty Burrell as Interpol agent Jean Pierre Napoleon.  Disney's "Muppets Most Wanted" is directed by James Bobin and produced by David Hoberman and Todd Lieberman. Bobin co-wrote the screenplay with Nicholas Stoller, who is also executive producer with John G. Scotti. Featuring music from Academy Award®-winning songwriter Bret McKenzie, "Muppets Most Wanted" hits the big screen March 21, 2014.

text: This looks alright. I mean, why allow Rick Gervais outside? He isn't funny. Tiny Fey is tolerable. Ty is great. Ray Liota is funny. Looks like they just shoe-horned in any modern actor for a shitty cameo. Not necessary. Also why are Rizzo, Gonzo and several other Muppets losing screen-time? The old movies were great because the Muppets were the focus and the humans helped out with some scenes. Now it's all celebrities doing nothing and they put Muppets in the scene. Barely any interesting interactions between them. Kills nostalgia and watch-ability of these movies.  Having said all that I'll probably see this eventually anyway. The last one was good, but I have my reservations with this one. We'll see I guess.

text: I haven't seen this yet but, I think instead of making movies that are mostly made up of celebrity cameos and fan service, they should work on creating a new Muppet Show (with a different celebrity host for each episode, like the original). They could create new skits, some new characters, musical guests (like SNL, or like Sesame Street has been doing the last few years), and it could have everything the original show had, only updated for a modern audience. I really think a show, if done right, could work better than the last few movies (which really feel like a love letter or tribute to the Muppets more than anything). I mean the last movie wasn't bad but, I felt like it could have been better.

text: ok, im gonna get into fights now but i am a muppet fan and I did not like the last muppet movie with amy adams. I like her but I just did not like the movie. it won awards for "am I a man or a muppet" but that song made me cringe. the badguy rapping made me leave the theater for a "bathroom break" because I felt it was so corny. anyway I went to see this "muppets most wanted" and I thought it was so much better. I came home to see the reviews and they all seem a little negative. they are acting like the other muppet film was better than "muppets most wanted". I disagree. I could watch "muppets most wanted" again right now, but I will never sit thru "the muppets 2011" again unless someone pays me for my time. if you like the muppets I would reccomend this film and if you hated "the muppets 2011" I want you to know this new movie is different than that.
